00:01:31.590 --> 00:01:37.070
 So, somewhere you have to sacrifice meaning to keep a good sound. 

00:01:37.070 --> 00:01:42.320
 And who is guilty of making a translation of a song so complicated? 

00:01:42.320 --> 00:01:45.350
 That is phonology. 

00:01:45.350 --> 00:01:48.569
 The phonology of a language is like its musical DNA 

00:01:48.569 --> 00:01:50.159
 and it has a primordial influence 

00:01:50.159 --> 00:01:53.759
 on how a melody of a song is written in a certain language. 

00:01:53.759 --> 00:01:57.549
 Even the specific way a baby cries has to do with how his mother speaks. 

00:01:57.549 --> 00:02:00.549
 There are two things that matter in phonology. 

00:02:00.549 --> 00:02:03.240
 The phonemes are the vowels and consonants that make the speech. 

00:02:03.240 --> 00:02:06.670
 and the prosody of a language is the way the phonemes come together 

00:02:06.670 --> 00:02:10.080
 to syllables, and sentences and their pronunciation 

00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:11.590
 to convey meaning there. 

00:02:11.590 --> 00:02:14.740
 It is the prosody of English that makes the difference between saying 

00:02:14.740 --> 00:02:19.880
 "Hey, you're HOT", and say "Hey, YOU'RE hot." 

00:02:20.900 --> 00:02:22.840
 But, back to music. 

00:02:22.840 --> 00:02:25.110
 It is the phonological system of a language 

00:02:25.110 --> 00:02:28.870
 that gives shape to the melody of a song originally written in that language. 

00:02:28.870 --> 00:02:30.799
 And if that song translates into a language 

00:02:30.799 --> 00:02:33.939
 with a completely different phonological system, 

00:02:33.939 --> 00:02:36.730
